INTRODUCTION</p><p>Every culture has its own image of man, which serves as a guideline for its development and maintenance in this world and in the hereafter. The image of man does not always have to be consciously known in full. It depends on the phase of development and need of the relevant culture how the image of man looks and which fragments are sharply formulated from time to time.</p><p>In the history of Indonesia, there have certainly been many images of man and there are still now. Every culture that came from outside brought its own image of man and the world and influenced the existing one. The influence was of course reciprocal.</p><p>Thus, with the arrival of the Hindus, the Hindu image of man and the world was also imported, which found expression in the Ramayana and Mahabharata. With Buddhism, a Buddhist image of man and the world came into being. Later came Islam and Christianity. All these images of man and the world were mixed and processed with the autochthonous. In an overview of Indonesia, there are areas where the original animistic image of man and the world is still held in honor, in other regions we find pure or more or less modified images of man and the world from Hinduism, Buddhism, Islam and Christianity. In the wajang stories we often see images of man and the world inserted that do not fit into the continuity of the Ramayana and the Mahabharata. These inserted, self-contained stories, make use of the popularity of the wajang in Javanese culture to reach the broad layer of the population, and show in their content an anti-propaganda against the Hindu image of man and the world. In particular, I mention here the stories: Dewa Ruci, Arjuna Wiwaha, Makuta Rama and Dipaningrat. In Javanese literature of the previous century, we encounter more or less</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-13-</p><p>developed images of man, such as the writings of Ronggowarsito and Wirjokoesosoemomo (1).</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>The classical, fixed-rule sequence of scenes and the entire show during the wajang performance also reveal to the viewer a human and world view (2), which may have existed in its primitive form even before the arrival of the Hindus.</p><p>Studies and lectures by the late Dr. Radjiman Wedyadiningrat, whom I personally knew, are well known in recent times. Especially the wajang story "Dewa Ruci", in which the hero Bima searches for the water of life, was the favorite topic of this versatile man, who gave all his strength to the freedom struggle, despite his advanced age and physical disability.</p><p>This dissertation draws its sources from books, writings, letters from and conversations and contact with people who seek the meaning of life and strive to achieve this meaning and purpose. So there have been three people who have provided the source for this dissertation. These three people are: R. Soenarto Mertowardojo, R. T. Hardjoprakoso (⍏ 1942) and R. Trihardono Soemodihardjo, of whom the former is the central figure.</p><p>From the presence of all these above-mentioned sources of human images, one would conclude that Soenarto would have built up his human and world view from all these data, as any scientist would have done. However, Soenarto did not work in this way. He knew all these existing sources no more or less than the average minor official. The last chapter deals with a comparative consideration of the place of the ego in the systems of Freud, Adler and Jung with that in the Indonesian human image</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-19-</p><p>II THE STRUCTURAL</p><p>When we establish a schema, as is depicted in this chapter (see schema I) of the relationship of the human being to the outside world and of the intrapsychic relationships, we have an overview of the human image as a visual aid to understand the anatomy and physiology of the human being as a spiritual being. In addition, this schema is a visual pied à terre to easily follow and understand the objectives of the Indonesian human image.</p><p>In dealing with the Indonesian human image and its meaning, we should always keep certain points in mind, and these are: 1. the nature of man, both structurally and functionally; 2. the nature of the outside world; 3. the sensory- psychological communication between man and the outside world; and 4. the inner communication between man and the transcendent.</p><p>All four of these points are considered from the standpoint of man as a spiritual being, who strives to manifest the transcendent Absolute in himself.</p><p>Both man and the world outside of him are dynamic, with man having the freedom to make a decision and to make a choice. When choosing an ideal image, there is a possibility that the ideal image is achieved, just as there is a possibility that the goal is not achieved and the man remains stuck or ends up on side roads.</p><p>Therefore, this human image also mentions a path as a guideline for the difficult process of human development. The ideal image is therefore nothing more than a man with qualities that have grown out of the man himself. These qualities have always been there. Only they are latent or in reduced form in the average man. There is continuity between the personality of the average man and that of the ideal image, the end stage of human being. Nothing is inserted or impregnated into the personality of man from the</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-20-</p><p>outside during development. No forces from the outside come into play that are alien to man and that are not of the man himself. When foreign forces from the outside come to us and work together in our body, then we end up on the wrong track. This is the essential difference between the Indonesian human image of Soenarto and certain other human images that we find in Indonesia.</p><p>The ideal image can still be achieved in this life. The teaching of this Indonesian human and world view.</p><p>The human being would consist of an essential immaterial principle and a material shell. (1) This immaterial principle is not localized anywhere in the body and is not bound to a specific organ, but it is indicated that the point of contact of the immaterial principle on the material must be in the vicinity of the heart (2). The place where we experience our deepest and finest feelings gives the gateway to this immaterial principle.</p><p>The starting point of this Indonesian human and world view is the Primordial Life, which is the source of all life and all matter (3). This Primordial Life is one and eternal, immaterial, permeates everything and holds everything within itself. It stands above time and space. It has no beginning and no end. Time and space were born from this Primordial Life. This is in essence one, but it manifests itself in three aspects. The first and highest aspect is the life that is absolutely still and static and is called <em>Suksma Kawekas</em>. The second aspect is the life that is dynamic, where activity is born from the static, it is called <em>Suksma Sejati</em>. The third aspect is the <em>Roh Suci</em>, the true soul of man, which can be understood as a spark or spark of <em>Suksma Kawekas</em>. The two bodies, both gross and subtle, are closely interwoven. One could metaphorically compare them to water and the steam above it. The influence between them is reciprocal.</p><p>The gross <em>bumi</em> and the subtle <em>langit</em> are divided into seven layers, which are not built next to each other, but within each other. THE FUNCTIONAL</p><p>During the development process of the human physical body, we see various vital centers emerge, each with its own sphere of action.</p><p>The <em>Tripurusa </em>is the essential immaterial center, which according to the Indonesian image of man, brings life to the human being and makes them aware that they are alive.</p><p>Furthermore, there is the <em>angen-angen</em>, created from the reflection of the <em>Tripurusa</em> in the physical body. The <em>angen-angen </em>forms the ego of the human being and has potential influence over the <em>rasa-pangrasa,</em> or <em>pangrasa</em> [feeling] for short, and the <em>nafsu</em> (1). The <em>angen-angen's</em> primary characteristic is sovereignty (albeit limited), and it is in constant contact with the <em>pangrasa</em>. The <em>angen-angen</em> actualizes a certain potential through its connection with the <em>nafsu</em> and the body's executive organs. The <em>angen-angen</em> is the carrier of individual consciousness. Through the intimate connection of the <em>angen-angen</em> with the <em>pangrasa</em> and the <em>nafsu</em>, the individual consciousness becomes associated with desire. The individual consciousness overshadows the Tripurusa's consciousness, making it latent. Because <em>Suksma Kawekas</em> is the primal form of all life, the consciousness carried by the <em>Tripurusa </em>is something collective. It is the collective consciousness.</p><p>Life is present everywhere, both in the micro- and macro-cosmos. There is unity and totality. Due to the individuality of the ego, the human being does not experience this totality. The ego's sovereignty distances itself from this existing unity and totality. Accepting this unity and totality as a higher sovereignty means subordinating one's own sovereignty. Due to individuality, there is separation, and this makes the human being, as it were, an exile from the primal form of life. In this</p><p>—-------(1)</p><p>(1) Soenarto c.s.: S.D. Hoofdstuk „Gumelaring Dumadi", blz. 62.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>-28-</p><p>exile, the ego has a central and directing function in relation to the <em>pangrasa</em>, the <em>nafsu</em>, and the executive organs. The <em>angen-angen</em> stimulates the activity of the <em>Nafsu</em> and is able to guide it in certain paths (2).</p><p>Outwardly, the ego acts as the representative of the entire body, which is also responsible for the activities of drive (<em>nafsu</em>) and feeling (<em>pangrasa</em>). But structurally, the ego is only formed by the <em>angen-angen</em>. The ego covers the feeling and drive like a veil.</p><p>The constructive parts of the angen-angen: <em>cipta</em>, <em>nalar</em> and <em>pangerti</em>, and the four forces of <em>nafsu-</em>drive: <em>lawamah</em>, <em>sufiah</em>, <em>amarah</em> and <em>mutmainah</em>, are called the brotherly forces of the ego (3). So there are seven brotherly forces. These brotherly forces unite into one integrated whole. The unification is usually not total, each of the seven still has a certain freedom of movement in relation to what is unified. If the unification is total, then the total unified force is called <em>Bayu Sejati</em> (4), and it is capable of producing supernatural abilities, such as clairvoyance, healing, telepathy, etc. For example, with the <em>Bayu Sejati</em> one could find a lost object without hesitation, drive blindfolded through a busy street, perform a dance one has never seen before, speak a foreign language one does not know; etc etc. The <em>Bayu Sejati</em> can be awakened at will. However, the total unification is subject to conditions (see also, chapter: On Self-Consciousness). The consciousness remains completely intact in the state of <em>Bayu Sejati</em>.</p><p>There is an integrative connection between the <em>Tripurusa</em>, the senses, the feeling and the drive. Given the fact that they can be considered centers of the human being, it depends on where the human being places the center of gravity of life, on the <em>Tripurusa</em>, on the senses, on the feeling or on the</p><p>-------(2-4)</p><p>(2) Soenarto cs: S.D. Hoofdstuk „Gumelaring</p><p>Dumadi", blz. 63.</p><p>(3) Soenarto: Aparte openbaring 1949.</p><p>(4) Soenarto cs: S.D. Hoofdstuk „Gumelaring Dumadi”, blz. 60.</p><p>-29-</p><p>drive. In principle, there are only two possibilities. Firstly, the center of gravity can be in the immaterial center, the <em>Tripurusa,</em> and secondly, in the physical body. In the body, the center of gravity can be with the <em>angen-angen</em> (intellectual faculties), or with the <em>pangrasa</em> (emotional qualities) or with the drive (willpower).</p><p>How does the cooperation between <em>angen-angen</em>, <em>pangrasa</em> and <em>nafsu</em> happen? The <em>nafsu</em>, as unconscious impulses, form the driving force or the engine that activates the <em>angen-angen</em> and the <em>pangrasa</em>. The <em>angen-angen</em> and the <em>pangrasa</em> are instruments or tools that lie in the conscious plane.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>The nafsu <em>lawamah</em> and <em>mutmainah</em> are polar opposites. The <em>Lawamah</em> is the egocentric inward drive, the <em>mutmainah</em> is the egocentric outward drive. The <em>sufiah</em> and the <em>amarah</em> can be considered auxiliary drives.</p><p>First, the <em>lawamah</em> produces an egocentric inward drive. The <em>nafsu sufiah</em> is the producer of the desire that is connected to this drive. This desire activates the <em>amarah</em>, which supports the desire and produces the willpower or perseverance to realize the desired. The combination of <em>lawamah</em>, <em>sufiah</em> and <em>amarah</em> is passed on to the <em>angen-angen</em>. <em>Cipta </em>creates an image of what is desired.</p><p><em>Nalar</em> associates this image with other images from the existing or from the momentary perception, and <em>pangrasa</em> has a clear overview of what is desired. Through the understanding by <em>pangerti,</em> the image of the desired is further sharpened and the <em>angen-angen</em> puts the senses on alert, stimulates the <em>nafsu</em> again to strengthen the desire, and mobilizes the executive organs, through which the desired can be achieved (5).</p><p>The desired object does not have to be a physical object. It can be something abstract, like a position, a certain level of development, a specific situation, a certain possibility of being, etc.</p><p>—-------(5)</p><p>(5) Soenarto: Aparte openbaring d.d. 1-VI'49.</p><p>-30-</p><p>The <em>mutmainah</em> cannot develop without the sufiah either. The combination of <em>mutmainah</em> and <em>sufiah</em> stimulates the desire for mercy, generosity, nobility, love of neighbor, and therefore the social and suprasocial tendencies (6).</p><p>Then the same procedure is followed with the <em>angen-angen</em>, the senses, and the executive organs.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>When the social and suprasocial <em>mutmainah</em> dominates, then the <em>lawamah</em> is overrun. The <em>lawamah</em> then becomes not an initiator and despot, but a willing subject and develops as physical strength, tolerance, capacity for endurance, strength to endure hardships (7). So there is conversion possible with the <em>lawamah</em>, which is not the case with the <em>mutmainah</em>.</p><p>The <em>angen-angen,</em> which through the senses takes cognizance of the external world, must regulate the <em>nafsu</em> so that there is a good relationship with and a good attitude towards the external world. The person must adapt to the external world and thereby must guide the nafsu's into manageable paths.</p><p>If the desired object is achieved, the body experiences a positive affect. If the desired object is lost, dead, broken, or not achieved, then the affect becomes negative. In that case, the unachieved desire with its associated images is stored in the angen-angen in the narrower sense (8). The overcrowding of the <em>angen-angen</em> in the narrower sense causes states of illness (neurosis, psychosis, psychosomatic illnesses), or it discharges itself in speech, gesticulation, and in dreams. The overcrowded <em>angen-angen</em> can be discharged without harmful consequences through an attitude of acceptance and resignation (9).</p><p>The dream is considered in this Indonesian image of man as an overflow of the overloaded <em>angen-angen</em>. Only a very small part of the number of dreams has a</p><p>—-------(6-9)</p><p>(6) Soenarto c.s. S.D. Hoofdstuk „Gumelaring Dumadi”, blz. 62, 63.</p><p>(7) Soenarto c.s. S.D. Hoofdstuk „Gumelaring Dumadi”, blz, 62, 63.</p><p>(8) Soenarto: Aparte openbaring d.d.1-VI-’49.</p><p>(9) Soenarto: Aparte openbaring d.d. 1-VI-’49.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>-31-</p><p>prophetic character, that is, the dream then contains a summarizing symbolic indication of what the dreamer will experience themselves in the near future (10). Jung does not use the word prophetic, but "pre-feeling" (11). And what the meaning of such a dream is, potentially only the person concerned knows, because the dream has his personal symbol. Only psychotherapists (<em>ahli budhi)</em> would be able to interpret such a dream (12).</p><p>As mentioned before, the ego's natural activity causes the <em>Tripurusa</em>'s consciousness to be overgrown and latent. The ego feels itself ruler of the body and also considers itself as such. When the nafsu as driving force is strong and the <em>angen-angen</em> is weak in providing direction, then the <em>angen-angen</em> adjusts to the <em>nafsu</em>. The <em>lawamah-sufiah</em> combination then dominates the <em>angen-angen</em> (13). The egocentric desires and longings then dominate the person.</p><p>When the person's reaction to the external world is colored by the hegemony of the <em>nafsu</em>, it is as if the person reacts with their passions. If the <em>angen-angen</em> dominates, then such a person reacts with their thinking abilities. If the <em>pangrasa </em>dominates, then they are a person of feelings.</p><p>If the <em>mutmainah</em> outweighs the <em>lawamah</em>, then the ego has a social and suprasocial orientation. With this orientation, the ego behaves in accordance with the conscience, which in the Indonesian image of man is thought to be built from all the person's phylogenetic and ontogenetic experiences, in which the <em>mutmainah</em> plays a large part. Through the social and suprasocial orientation, the ego easily directs itself towards the <em>Tripurusa</em>, the immaterial center. When the <em>angen-angen</em> is directed towards the <em>Tripurusa</em>, the image choice, association, and understanding are in har-</p><p>—-------(10-13)</p><p>(10) Soenarto: Aparte openbaring d.d, 1-VI-'49.</p><p>(1I) C. G. Jung: Seelenprobleme der Gegenwart, Rascher &amp; Cie A.G. Verlag, Zürich, blz. 99.</p><p>(12) Soenarto: Aparte openbaring d.d. 1-VI-49,</p><p>(13) Soenarto cs.: S.D. Hoofdstuk „Gumelaring Dumadi”, blz. 64, 65.</p><p>-32-</p><p>mony with the <em>Tripurusa</em>. There comes a "higher" ego, a "higher" <em>cipta</em>, a "higher" <em>nalar</em>, and a "higher" <em>pangerti</em> (14). In this way, the center of gravity of the person's life shifts to the <em>Rahsa Jati</em> (true consciousness of the <em>Tripurusa</em>).</p><p>Where is the <em>Rahsa Jati</em>?</p><p>"When someone is transported by the feeling that life, which is in every living being, manifests itself in them, then they can indicate where the <em>Rahsa Jati</em> is" (15).</p><p>—-------(14-15)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(14) Soenarto c.s: S.D. Hoofdstuk „Gumelaring Dumadi”, blz. 65.</p><p>(15). Soenarto: Aparte openbaring d.d. 1-VI-'49.</p><p>-33-</p><p>IV. THE AVERAGE MEN</p><p>As we have seen in the chapters "The Structural" and "The Functional," man as a totality consists of three separate forms of being that are intimately connected with each other. From the outside to the inside, we have the gross, subtle, and immaterial forms of being.</p><p>The gross form of being is the world of the sensory, where physical and chemical processes take place. This corresponds to the "Sinnlichräumliche Welt" of Karl Jaspers (1). We could compare this world of being to the biological world. The connection with the rest of the external world occurs through the senses and vital functions, such as eating and drinking, excretory functions, breathing, and heat exchange. The life force in this gross form of being is formed by the <em>nafsu</em>'s: <em>lawamah, sufiah, amarah</em>, and <em>mutmainah</em>. Here, the <em>lawamah</em> is the drive for self-preservation, and the <em>mutmainah</em> is the drive for the sense of community in which the individual finds himself. The <em>sufiah</em> is the source of desire and longing, and the <em>amarah</em> is the force to pursue desire and longing. The atmosphere in which the <em>nafsu</em>'s play out is unconscious. The existence of the gross body is bound by time and space and lasts from conception to death.</p><p>The subtle form of being is the world of the psychic. Since the angen-angen dominates there, we can also call it the angen-angen world or the ego-world because the ego occupies a central place in the <em>angen-angen</em>. This world corresponds to the "seelisch-kulturelle Welt" of Karl Jaspers (2). This ego-world is conscious, and because this consciousness is limited and therefore there is individuality, it is limited consciousness, individual consciousness, or personal consciousness.</p><p>—-------(1-2)</p><p>(1) Karl Jaspers: Psychologie der Weltanschauungen. Verlag von Julius Springer, Berlin, 1925, blz. 154.</p><p>(2) Karl Jaspers: idem, blz. 170.</p><p>-34-</p><p>The subtle form of being is bound by time and space, but its existence is not fixed to the gross form of being. The possibility of the ego-world existing after physical death is accepted in the Indonesian image of man.</p><p>This ego-world communicates with the external world through the senses. The existence of this ego-world does not depend on the vital functions of the gross body, such as eating, drinking, urination, defecation, breathing, and heat regulation. The bridge between the gross and subtle forms of being is formed by the <em>pangrasa</em>, the emotions, or the feeling life. The unconscious nafsu is connected to the <em>angen-angen</em>, so that <em>nafsu</em> activities can penetrate the personal consciousness. Therefore, three complexes or centers play out in the subtle form of being, which are themselves active and have a certain connection to each other. These three complexes are responsible for the vitality of the subtle form of being and are therefore called vitality centers. They are the <em>angen-angen</em> or intellectual abilities with the ego as the core, the <em>pangrasa</em> or the feeling life, and the <em>nafsu</em> as the will or desire life.</p><p>Therefore, this ego-world has needs, which are determined by the needs of these centers. Karl Jaspers classifies these needs under the cultural life of man (3). There is a psychic interaction with the external world, and through this interaction, which is a contact and an encounter, the <em>angen-angen</em>, pangrasa, and <em>nafsu</em> grow. Experiences accumulate. The person who has gone through thousands of experiences and thousands of pains gathers data for a conception and an image of how to live and how to view the world around them. They form a human and world image. This human and world image is their guide, their template, for how to best get by, what to do and what not to do to maintain their existence and their balance.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>—-------(3)</p><p>(3) Karl Jaspers: idem, biz. 185.</p><p>-35-</p><p>This human and world image is his conscience. This conscience arises, therefore, through the encounter of the external world with the human, who has at their disposal the unconscious <em>nafsu</em> and the conscious <em>angen-angen</em> with the <em>pangrasa</em>. This conscience is stored in the angen-angen in a narrower sense, which is unconscious but has a different location, therefore structured differently, than the unconscious <em>nafsu</em>. Certain facets of the conscience can be made conscious as needed. The consciously made facets of the conscience come as thought images in the <em>angen-angen</em> and from here they exert their influence on the emotional and volitional life and on the executive organs. Thus, the conscience uses the existing hierarchical channels to unfold its activity.</p><p>The third form of being is the world of immaterial life, the <em>Tripurusa</em>, which has its point of contact in the <em>Rahsa Jati</em>. This <em>Rahsa Jati</em> is not an organic thing, it is a certain climate in the psychic life, also referred to as the essence of the feeling life. It is the gateway or threshold to the immaterial possibility of being. This can be compared to the "metaphysical world" of Karl Jaspers (4). In order to pass from the psychic form of being to this immaterial possibility of being, there must be a continuity. This continuity is formed by consciousness. This immaterial possibility of being is not bound to matter, and therefore not to limitations in time and spatiality. Once consciousness finds itself in the immaterial possibility of being, then consciousness is no longer bound to anything, and therefore also not individually limited. In that state, consciousness is universal and collective. It is the world of the collective conscious. This world is both within and outside the human being. There is no longer any need for communication between the inner and outer worlds. Senses, which are inherently limited, are superfluous. The collective conscious is a totality. Therefore, there are no more needs, because there is no longer any possibility</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>of growth. Everything that has a limited character of the psychic life</p><p>—-------(4)</p><p>(4) Karl Jaspers: idem, blz. 185.</p><p>-36-</p><p>disappears. The personal limitations of the <em>angen-angen</em>, the <em>pangrasa</em>, and the <em>nafsu</em> disappear. There is no longer any personal psychic life. The immaterial center acts directly on the executive organs. Because there is no longer any psychic interaction with the external world, the senses are only used in the motor functions.</p><p>Therefore, within a human being, three worlds are present simultaneously, in one another, and alongside one another.</p><p>From "outside" to "inside," we can say that the gross, subtle, and immaterial worlds exist. We can also speak of the biological, the psychic, and the spiritual forms of being. We can also illuminate this order through a facet: namely, from the collective unconscious, through the personal unconscious and personal conscious to the collective conscious, or also from the unlimited pleasurable through the limited pleasurable to the pleasureless.</p><p>Each person places the center of gravity differently. And each possibility of being has its forms and demands, its own style of existence. If the center of gravity lies in the gross possibility of being, then the <em>nafsu</em> functions, the biological, dominate. If the center of gravity lies in the psychic form of being, then the <em>angen-angen</em> and/or the <em>pangrasa</em> dominate. In the immaterial form of being, there is no more individual life. Jung would say that all expressions of such a person are impersonal or archetypal (5). There is a possible shift in the center of gravity from the gross world to the immaterial life, the metaphysical possibility of being. With this shift, needs, insights, attitudes, and lifestyle change.</p><p>By following a certain way of life, we can shift the center of gravity. Each shift is only possible by accepting a new lifestyle with the abandonment of the old. Thus, there is a path to be called from the gross</p><p>—------- (5)</p><p>(5) C. G. Jung: Die Beziehungen zwischen dem Ich und dem Unbewussten, Rascher Verlag Zürich und Leipzig, 1938, blz. 99.</p><p>-37-</p><p>to the immaterial possibility of being. This path is marked by changes in activity and reactions from all present centers and by a resistance from those centers themselves, according to the law of inertia. The immaterial possibility of being can therefore be conceived as an endpoint and goal on this path. It can be considered an ideal image of the human being. In the Indonesian image of man</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>and world, this ideal image is potentially attainable for everyone.</p><p>The <em>angen-angen</em> arises from the reflection of the <em>Tripurusa</em> in the material body, as for example, moonlight is a reflection of sunlight. Because the <em>Tripurusa</em> consists of three hierarchical relationships, we also see three facets in the <em>angen-angen</em>, which stand in a hierarchical relationship to each other.</p><p>The absolute sovereignty of the <em>Tripurusa </em>manifests itself in the limited individual sovereignty of the <em>angen-angen</em>. The "I" of the <em>angen-angen</em> makes the human being feel that they are alive. The feeling of being alive is accompanied by pleasure, and therefore the pleasureless consciousness of the <em>Tripurusa</em> is overgrown and becomes latent. On the path from the gross to the immaterial possibility of being, it is therefore about unearthing this latent collective consciousness of the <em>Tripurusa</em>. The power to leave the pleasurable is formed by the <em>mutmainah</em> in cooperation with the <em>sufiah</em>.</p><p>This combination is the power to pursue the higher and is called <em>asmara sufi.</em> It is the longing for the social and supra-social. In society, one finds both types who place the center of gravity on the gross and types who place the center of gravity on the subtle possibility of being. With the current state of humanity, the types who have reached the immaterial possibility of being are a high exception.</p><p>In the prototype of the human being who places the center of gravity on the <em>angen-angen</em>, sovereignty comes to the fore strongly. They are individualistic. In addition to the tendency towards individualism, sovereignty results in a love for freedom of</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-38-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>thought and at the same time a dislike of coercion, bondage, the authority of another, and tradition.</p><p>Another function of the <em>angen-angen</em> is that of a grasping organ towards the external world. This allows humans to control the material. The <em>angen-angen</em> is dynamic and restless. Standstill for the <em>angen-angen</em> means death. The <em>angen-angen</em> seizes the external world, schematizes and categorizes it, splits it into ever smaller parts. Sovereignty tolerates no co-sovereignty. Since no other sovereignty is tolerated, the <em>angen-angen</em> desubjectifies everything it grasps. The surrounding world is considered objectively, and that which is the absolute subject, the <em>Tripurusa</em>, is declared non-existent. The <em>angen-angen</em> self as subject is maintained. This last point is understandable, although not consistent. If the self were consistent, it would also have to declare its own subjectivity non-existent. To dethrone the sovereignty of others, this type sees its fellow humans as desubjectified, therefore objective. For the <em>angen-angen</em>, it is either being or not being. There is no middle ground. That's why the prototype cannot put itself in the situation of another. No consideration is used with the other. The other is tolerated as long as he benefits the existence of their own sovereignty. There are no territorial grounds of another that one should instinctively stay out of. There is nothing sacred that must be respected. There is no tolerance. Fear is alien to this type. It dares anything. Nothing can stop it. The <em>angen-angen</em> gives the appearance of power, authority, and responsibility. The <em>angen-angen</em> type actually has no ultimate goal, is always in function, and focuses on performance. The best proof for the <em>angen-angen</em> that the external world is not sovereign is the decimation and analysis of that which falls under its reach. Science is the result of the unbridled restlessness and activity of the angen-angen, until science reaches a point that is completely subjective. Then the <em>angen-angen</em> can no longer grasp and split. Then the</p><p>—-------(-)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>-39-</p><p>point is reached where the <em>angen-angen</em> recognizes its limits and must surrender.</p><p>In the prototype, the <em>pangrasa</em> and the <em>nafsu</em> are used to support sovereignty. The <em>pangrasa</em> is reduced to an indicator that is only directly beneficial to the body, therefore serving as positive and negative affect. The <em>nafsu</em> is the engine and driving force that serves this prototype.</p><p>The <em>pangrasa</em> is the center that creates, maintains, and conserves the psychic climate. Its character is encompassing, absorbing, and nurturing. Everything that fills the psychic climate is clouded and spared for the sake of the climate itself. The sovereignty of others is fully respected. The subject is everything, even things are subjectivized. As a result, the relationships between them are also subjectivized. There is no objectivity, everything for the sake of the atmosphere. This must never be disturbed, even if it harms the self in a psychic, material, or physical sense. There is complete and utter tolerance.</p><p>In addition to creating and maintaining the psychic climate, a primary characteristic is the binding function. This emphasizes the coherence of the subjects. In contrast to the <em>angen-angen</em>, where the individual themselves is illuminated (it is as if they are or are not), the <em>pangrasa</em> emphasizes the relationship that is felt (it is close or distant). The individuals are equally important (6). The synthesizing <em>pangrasa</em> tries to encompass as much as possible with the climate. Because there are different facets in the world that are polar opposites, the <em>pangrasa</em> always tries to find the greatest common divisor and at the same time the smallest common multiple, until the <em>pangrasa</em> reaches a point where the entire world must be encompassed with everything in it. Here the function of the <em>pangrasa</em> ends, when the greatest common divisor is also the smallest common multiple.</p><p>—-------(6)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(6). C. G. Jung: Psychologische Typen, Rascher Verlag, blz. 430.</p><p>-40-</p><p>In this prototype, the <em>angen-angen</em> is rudimentary. The grasping organ is not used and confines itself to the reflective observation of that which falls within the field of vision. As a result, this type has no hold on the world outside itself. It is contemplative. It is static, conservative, and concerned with traditional matters. The <em>nafsu</em> is also the engine and driving force here.</p><p>The <em>nafsu</em> is the center of desires, cravings, and bodily strength. The motor organs come into motion when the result of their action gives a clear positive affect. In this prototype, both the <em>asmara sufi</em> and the <em>lawamah-sufiah</em> combination only work on the basis of a direct reward.</p><p>The <em>angen-angen</em> and the <em>pangrasa</em> are, in this type, respectively intended to secure a simple existence and to create a sense of well-being and safety throughout life.</p><p>The <em>Tripurusa</em> is the man's non-materially bound fourth center. The <em>Roh Suci</em>, as the true soul of man, lord and master in the body, makes use of the <em>angen-angen</em> to subdue the <em>nafsu</em>. This subduing is aimed at fulfilling the duty to direct oneself towards <em>Suksma Kawekas</em> via <em>Suksma Sejati</em>.</p><p>Towards the <em>nafsu, Roh Suci</em> is the ruler, towards <em>Suksma Sejati</em> the subject. By fulfilling both these duties, this type succeeds in letting the <em>angen-angen </em>and the <em>pangrasa </em>perform the vital tasks for the body and keeping them in check for the rest. There is a voluntary self-restriction and asceticism with the full preservation of the ability to fully utilize the <em>angen-angen</em>, the <em>pangrasa</em>, and the <em>nafsu</em> at any moment to grasp the outside world.</p><p>For the purpose of devotion to <em>Suksma Kawekas</em> via <em>Suksma Sejati</em>, the cooperation of <em>pangrasa</em> and <em>angen-angen</em> is used to distinguish subject from object and prepare the climate for the meeting of <em>Suksma Sejati </em>with <em>Roh Suci</em>. In this type, the three other</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-41-</p><p>vitality centers are not reduced in their functions. On the contrary, the functions and the connection between them are fully developed and utilized in a way that cannot be more efficient. In the complete and unconditional humility of <em>Roh Suci</em>, without any reminder of any individual limitation, <em>Roh Suci</em> is absorbed into <em>Suksma Sedjati</em>.</p><p>Due to the constant accumulation of new experiences, the human image and worldview also change, so that there is always a distance between the momentary being of the human and their human image as conscience. This difference makes it so that a stimulus is felt to bridge this gap. On its own, this difference will not be felt as too great, because otherwise the effective stimulus would be absent. This happens when a human image is forced upon someone that does not correspond to the state of being of the person involved.</p><p>There is an automatism in humans that arises from the "illumination" of the angen-angen by the conscience. This automatism, as it were, holds a mirror to our own <em>angen-angen</em>, our emotions and desires, so that we can discover their defective state. It is a magic mirror, because the discovered deficiency is always large enough on the one hand to make the person reflect and become active, but on the other hand not large enough to take away all illusions and hope or to be felt as too great a trauma.</p><p>Becoming aware of the difference between the momentary state of being and the image of conscience evokes a certain feeling of guilt, which has to be redeemed in one way or another. The penance consists of a directing oneself, a surrendering, an offering oneself to the ideal human image, which has a certain authority. The feeling of guilt is an expression of responsibility that shines from the conscience.</p><p>Directing oneself towards the conscience also means an appeal to the conscience. In the Indonesian human image, the conscience is the <em>Tripurusa</em> for the human, who has permanently shifted the center of gravity in the <em>Tripurusa</em>. This conscience is a state of</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-42-</p><p>consciousness that is above every emotion, every formation and intellect, above every desire, longing and function of will, and yet has certain characteristics in relation to both the human and their environment. These characteristics arise because the human views the <em>Tripurusa</em> from the standpoint of limitation and gives it names from the vocabulary of limitation. When a human makes an appeal to this conscience, it is as if they place their state of being and that of their environment against a backdrop of the Limitless and Unutterable, whereby the relationship between the human and that backdrop is seen simultaneously. The <em>Tripurusa</em> is not only a conscience that is but an image, but it is Life itself, which actively</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>approaches the human and leads and helps them onward. The appeal will never be in vain.</p><p>Humans form images from the external world in their angen-angen. These images from their observations are, as it were, the external world itself and their relationship to it, which they preserve as thoughts, opinions, judgments, etc. Thus, humans have the substitution of the external world directly at their disposal and can do with it what they want. They can work with it, play with it, and connect their emotions to it. But because of this, there is again a certain dependence of the self on the angen-angen content, the preserved external world. It then becomes as if those thoughts, opinions, associations, judgments, etc. possess sovereignty.</p><p>On the one hand, humans can strengthen their sovereignty with the <em>angen-angen</em>, on the other hand, the <em>angen-angen</em> contents gain their own sovereignty against the self. These <em>angen-angen</em> contents can activate autochthonous desires and impulses of will and evoke emotions that bring unrest.</p><p>Just as humans set themselves up against the external world with the <em>asmara sufi (-laya)</em>, so must they also direct themselves towards their own <em>angen-angen</em> contents if they want to seek peace and balance.</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-43-</p><p>The thought of death can bring peace (7). This also means a direction towards a state without desires, thoughts, and emotions. It also arouses a longing to leave the life lived so far and begin a new one, in accordance with the Will of Life.</p><p>The desire for a state where the ego no longer exercises its sovereign rights, but is even willing to surrender them and merge into a monotonous relationship with the external world without accents, is not the same as a desire to destroy the body, in which the ego still exists. This also means that the human withdraws from their <em>angen-angen</em> and enters a position where they do not use their <em>cipta</em> and <em>nalar</em>. The <em>cipta </em>and<em> nalar</em>, which are located in the cerebrum, capture the stimuli that reach the human from the external world via the senses. It is the <em>cipta</em> that makes contact with the nafsu, through which all kinds of desires are awakened, and also with the <em>pangrasa</em>, through which the affects participate in the reaction. The <em>nalar</em> associates images into endless fantasies (9). Without the <em>cipta</em> and <em>nalar</em>, and therefore without contact with the cerebrum, the human comes into a position where there are no images. There is then peace and quiet. Adopting a positive attitude of love and responsibility, which does not discriminate and is not personal; 3. Directing oneself towards the Impersonal within the self, without making use of representations, expectations, or any personal desire.</p><p>It takes a lot of courage to carry out the above. The old, that has become familiar to the human and to which he has become attached, must be abandoned in order to enter a state of being, which is often not understood by the environment.</p><p>Reaching the state of Roh Suci is an ability that every human being potentially has within themselves (11).</p><p>The relationship to the Boundless and Unnamable keeps the three vitality centers focused on a point that lies outside</p><p>—-------(10-11)</p><p>(10) Soenarto c.s.: S.D. It comes as something autochthonous, from the depths of our being.</p><p>2. It is independent of time and place.</p><p>3. The person involved experiences a feeling of great peace and happiness that lingers for some time.</p><p>7. There is a feeling of certainty and truthfulness.</p><p>8. There are no physical sensations of power or anything else, except as described in points 6 and 7.</p><p>9. No external force is involved.</p><p>10. Hoofdstuk „Gumelaring Dumadi”, blz. 65.</p><p>-50-</p><p>trarily made to do something and also arbitrarily commanded to stop.</p><p>We have said that the hidden powers were those of the angen-angen, the <em>pangaribawa</em>, the <em>prabawa</em>, and the <em>kamayan</em>, and that the <em>kamayan</em> in particular was a special power. Hoofdstuk „Dalan Rahaju”, blz. 169.</h2><p>-53-</p><h2>V THE IDEAL IMAGE</h2><h2>The ideal image is that particular state of consciousness in which all individual consciousness, along with all its associated psychic activities, has transitioned into the collective consciousness. To understand this better, recall that an average person possesses three levels of consciousness: The gross physical body (associated with the collective unconscious), the subtle or psychic life (associated with the individual conscious), the metaphysical life (associated with the collective conscious), these levels can interact and even merge. Within this context, the ideal image reflects the permanent manifestation of the collective conscious, eliminating any possibility of regressing back to the individual or collective unconscious.</h2><h2><a id="_m7xymru0l882"></a>In the average person, the central focus lies within the individual conscious, encompassing all its psychic activities. While the collective unconscious and collective conscious occasionally make contact with and send messages to the individual conscious, they don't represent the primary focus of life. The "ego" serves as the regulating complex within the average person. Despite the potential for experiencing a sense of individual totality, both the collective unconscious and collective conscious maintain autonomy relative to this individual existence. They are interconnected with the individual conscious but retain a degree of freedom within this dynamic. Reaching the collective conscious state, which represents the ultimate goal of human striving, results in the dissolution of both the individual and collective unconscious. The collective conscious emerges as a transcendent, Absolute totality. The individual's psychic life ceases to exist in its previous form. Instincts become solely associated with vital functions like hunger, thirst, and sleep, confined to physical needs without influencing the spiritual life. In this state of the ideal image, the will functions, emotional life, and logos all converge within the collective conscious. Any prior differentiation between will, feeling, and logos vanishes. The human being practices not forming any images in their thoughts during prayer.</p><p>The <em>cipta, </em>as the reflection of the <em>Roh Suci, </em>is the image-forming function within the <em>angen-angen</em>.
