The reflection of the <em>Roh Suci </em>is recalled by its source, or in other words, the human being can live without relying on the<em> cipta. </em>One can also view the Liberation process as overcoming the obstacles presented by the constructive elements of the<em> angen-angen.</em></p><p>Between the physical body and the<em> Roh Suci l</em>ies the <em>cipta, </em>with the <em>pangaribawa </em>as its reflection and weapon, which the<em> Roh Suci</em> uses to control the body. Between the <em>Roh Suci </em>and <em>Suksma Sejati </em>resides reason, along with its attribute, the <em>prabawa.</em> Between <em>Suksma Sejati </em>and <em>Suksma Kawekas </em>lies the <em>pangerti </em>with the<em> kamayan, </em>which reflects<em> Suksma Kawekas. Suksma Sejati </em>must overcome this reflection to reach<em> Suksma Kawekas.</em></p><p>To achieve liberation from material attachment, a person must practice setting aside the image-forming function. This function shapes the person's perception of the world according to their specific beliefs, ideas, traditions, and biases. However, life cannot be confined to any specific form. Therefore, individuals must break free from their preconceived notions, traditions, and rigid</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-83-</p><p>perspectives. The<em> cipta </em>operates by shaping and forming. Utilizing the<em> cipta </em>strengthens one's sense of sovereignty. However, living beyond the function of the <em>cipta</em> means accepting the world as it presents itself during encounters,</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>without selection or judgment. As a result, the sense of individual sovereignty gradually dissolves.</p><p>The human who has reached the state of <em>Roch Sutji </em>must next overcome the reason with the<em> prabawa</em>. Asking questions and seeking explanations are products of reason. The "how" and "why" of life, and the choice of a specific life path, are abandoned. The human being withdraws from the law of cause and effect known as Karma. They strive not to create Karma, even though they know how they could live a comfortable life in material terms.</p><p>If they are one with <em>Suksma Sejati, </em>they stand outside of Karma. Their actions, whether good or bad in the eyes of others, do not create Karmic consequences.</p><p>In the transition from <em>Suksma Sejati </em>to<em> Suksma Kawekas, </em>the <em>pangerti </em>must be overcome. The human's function as <em>Guru Sejati</em>, the True Teacher and Leader, the Light of the world, is abandoned in order to return to the Primordial Existence, where neither Policy nor Idea has yet been born.</p><p>The devotion of the <em>Rahsa Jati </em>is the devotion of the human who has reached the state of <em>Roh Suci</em>. This has already been explained previously.</p><p>All these phases, both hierarchically and structurally, are merely orientations for our rational mind. The human personality does not have a fixed point of equilibrium. The center of gravity fluctuates, and the level of being human varies greatly. Therefore, no fixed rules or regulations can be determined. Each individual must decide for themselves and, through self-observation against the backdrop of the ideal image, find out what is</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-84-</p><p>best for them, so that they do not overestimate or underestimate themselves.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>For every human being, regardless of their individual characteristics, the path to Liberation remains open. Each person has their own unique opportunities and perspectives. There is no single "shortcut" or faster path. Ultimately, the shortest path is determined by one's willingness to offer up their ego on the altar of the Impersonal.</p><p>Regarding point 3: Mercy and helpfulness based on love for one's neighbor is the best translation of the concept known as<em> budi darma. </em>It is a quality inherent to the human being who wholeheartedly helps those in need.</p><p><em>Budi darma </em>serves as the proper method for self-purification. Only pure feelings cultivated through <em>budi darma </em>can make prayer truly meaningful. The aim of this purification process is to keep the journey towards Liberation active and ongoing. This purification strengthens one's faith. It is crucial to maintain the purity of one's feelings as they act as the carriers of vows made to the<em> Tripurusa</em>. Only within pure feelings can truthfulness and a genuine love for truth blossom, allowing individuals to perceive the essence of things with clear discernment, unclouded by self-serving inclinations.</p><p>Helping others is not the monopoly of a specific class of wealthy individuals, nor is receiving help restricted to the group of the poor. This is because <em>darma </em>can be offered not only in the form of money or goods, but also in the form of physical assistance or advice. Even those who are poor can practice<em> darma. </em>Anyone can find themselves in a situation where they require some form of help, regardless of who it comes from. <em>Darma</em> should be appropriate for the need and not exceed the capacity of the helper, meaning it shouldn't hinder their own societal obligations. Each individual must determine</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-85-</p><p>the extent of their <em>darma </em>practice based on their own capacity. The nature of the help also depends on the circumstances. What one has in excess of a reasonable existence for themselves can be given in<em> darma. </em>If one is wealthy, then they can offer material goods. If one possesses knowledge, they can offer advice. If one is physically strong, they can help with labor. However, if a person lacks<em> narima</em> (acceptance), they cannot come to the realization that they have enough for themselves and their family. Consequently, their feelings cannot embody the essence of truthfulness and faith, even if they have the intention to penetrate the core of faith and truthfulness. In this way, they will never be able to achieve true devotion because their feelings are not pure and they do not purify themselves. <em>Darma</em> that is still governed by rules, obligations, and doesn't arise spontaneously from within is not yet perfect, even though it may be very useful and commendable.</p><p>The qualities of the <em>Tripurusa </em>should be kept in mind by humans and constantly strengthened within themselves so that they can be reflected upon and lived according to, becoming a facet of our conscience that shows us</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>the way and calls us to purification. The rules and regulations of the<em> darma</em> are there to provide people with support and guidance in its practice until they are no longer led by restrictive bonds and already know the course to their goal: through self-purification to be one with the All-Merciful.</p><p>Providing help without a trace of expectation, such as making a name for oneself, becoming known, or expecting help in return, is in accordance with the Will of <em>Suksma Kawekas</em>. The gift that someone offers to another from the bottom of their purified heart should be accepted, if at least that gift would not cause difficulties. If someone else could benefit more from that gift, it is desirable and good to pass that gift on later. Giving help to others should not just be a matter</p><p>—-------(-)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>-86-</p><p>of giving something as a ceremonial gesture, but should indeed be a realization of love for one's neighbor, so that the human being can understand and experience the Unity and Indivisibility of Life and thereby truly bear witness to the Confession.</p><p>4. Since there are instincts in the body that naturally move towards "evil", the human being should reflect on not letting these <em>nafsu </em>run free. All <em>nafsu, </em>both "good" and "bad", are forces of our body that give the body the capacity to carry out the orders of the <em>Roh Suci </em>in the context of the Will of <em>Suksma Kawekas</em> and also to achieve that which we personally desire. Therefore, the human being should not neglect his physical body, on the contrary, reasonable care should be taken of it.</p><p>The <em>angen-angen </em>means the<em> nafsu. </em>If one considers the<em> nafsu </em>as the bed of a river, then the <em>angen-angen</em> is the water. The human being can dam the river and not let the water flow according to the natural bed, but give it a new bed that is useful for the human being and in harmony with the Will of<em> Suksma Kawekas</em>. After all, in the beginning the bed was also created by the "choice" of the flowing water, as a mountain stream rushes to the valley and chooses its course only from the given geographical conditions, thus according to the water's own natural course.</p><p>The <em>angen-angen </em>changes the course of the <em>nafsu</em> by constantly thinking in a certain train of thought and in a certain direction. In the beginning it is of course still difficult and the associated affect is negative. This affect eventually becomes positive, so that the direction and atmosphere of thinking becomes ingrained and the nafsu is curbed. Habit has become second nature.</p><p>The formation and change of a character begins with the <em>angen-angen. </em>That is why a human being must</p><p>—-------(-)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>-87-</p><p>start to censor his thoughts and direct them in a certain direction, in the direction of the qualities of the<em> Tripurusa.</em></p><p>The will that arises from a <em>nafsu </em>is called<em> karep,</em> the Will of<em> Suksma Kawekas </em>is called<em> Karsa. </em>The <em>Karsa </em>is not bound by any condition in its origin. A<em> karep </em>is always accompanied or followed by images or concepts in the<em> angen-angen</em>.</p><p>The control of nafsu only relates to that nafsu which does not conform to the teachings of <em>Suksma Sejati.</em> One must train the sufiah nafsu to desire good things.</p><p>If this is very difficult because the bad habit is deeply ingrained, then control must be facilitated by reducing eating, drinking, sleeping, and sexual drive. Reducing these life needs should only go so far as to keep the memory of our striving alive and not harm the body. After all, the body must bring the human being to the goal. Fasting (in all its qualities) is therefore always subordinate to the goal. It should not become a ceremony, nor should it become the main goal solely from practice. The seven brothers must be raised in harmony and not mistreated. They are brothers, not slaves, but certainly not masters. With constant repetition, the human being will learn to feel the dosage of asceticism himself, until the nafsu is completely directed towards his thoughts, feelings, and aspirations, and there is no longer any obstacle due to vital bodily functions.</p><p>Asceticism is a powerful weapon to detach oneself from the material, provided it is properly dosed. The dosage is determined by the wisdom one obtains by strictly following the <em>Trisila</em>. Asceticism in any form is not yet effective in its full value when it is still bound by rules. Asceticism must flow from an inner need, without being accompanied by expectations of any worldly nature, such as power, wealth, respect, and awe from followers,</p><p>—-------(-)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>-88-</p><p>or the acquisition of magical powers. It is pointless to retreat into seclusion and live in asceticism, isolate oneself, and thereby avoid the obligation to help humanity in the search for a way and a form of society where people can understand and respect each other.</p><p>5. The state in which the center of gravity lies in the <em>Rahsa Jati </em>is the beginning of<em> Budi Luhur.</em></p><p>In this state, there is a psychological climate in which the human being fully masters the qualities of <em>"narima, sabar, temen, </em>and <em>rila," </em>understands and realizes the Confession, makes devotion a way of life, and is impersonally loving and just towards the outside world. It is the human being who is on the eve of Unity with<em> Suksma Sejati </em>and no longer needs to use his <em>angen-angen</em> to control his body.</p><p>Shifting the center of gravity towards the <em>Tripurusa </em>is done by withdrawing reflection, so that the hold on the physical body, which the<em> angen-angen</em> also is, is released. This does not mean that the physical body is left to its own fate. It only means that the human being has abandoned his affinity for the material. Therefore, the functioning of the <em>angen-angen </em>can also be interpreted as an indication of affinity for the world. If the <em>angen-angen </em>disappears, then there is nothing more that hinders Unity. It only depends on the Will of <em>Suksma Kawekas </em>when this happens. Unity can also be seen from the standpoint of the Three-in-One (<em>Tripurusa</em>) receding into the Two-in-One (<em>Suksma Kawekas - Suksma Sejati</em>) and finally into the Absolute One (<em>Suksma Kawekas). </em>The human being who is not influenced by the existence of the <em>angen-angen</em> and the<em> nafsu</em> attains the qualities of <em>Suksma Sejati.</em></p><p>If we illuminate the wording of the <em>Roh Suci, </em>then its</p><p>—--------(-)</p><p>-89-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>essence is a Self-sacrifice of <em>Suksma Kawekas. </em>This self-sacrifice also governs the entire picture of Liberation, starting from the sacrifice of the I-consciousness of the physical to the complete surrender of<em> Suksma Sejati </em>to<em> Suksma Kawekas.</em> This All-sacrifice is something immanent, beyond all comprehension. Therefore, the state of <em>budi luhur </em>reached after the human being perfectly follows the <em>Trisila, </em>the <em>Pancasila</em>, and the implementing regulations is also above all rationalization. Obedience is the beginning of <em>temen </em>(truthfulness), which leads to<em> narima </em>(acceptance), which in turn brings about<em> sabar </em>(patience), and <em>sabar </em>leads the person to<em> rila </em>(willingness to let go). Only when this phase of<em> rila </em>is embodied can we enter the state of <em>budi luhur</em>.</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-90-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>VII ON THE <em>DEWAS</em></p><p>(1)</p><p>Soenarto and his colleagues wrote about the<em> dewas </em>or <em>djawata </em>in the books <em>"Gumelaring Dumadi" </em>(The Process of Creation) and<em> "Tunggal Sabda" </em>(The Same Word), from which this chapter largely draws its core.</p><p>The<em> dewas </em>are creations of <em>Suksma Kawekas</em> who stand between humans and animals. Their bodies are made of elemental fire, and they live wherever the element of fire is present. According to this Indonesian worldview, the universe consists of a gross material and a subtle material part. The gross material part, like the human body, is called <em>bumi </em>and also has seven layers. Similarly, the subtle material part, also called<em> langit</em>, is seven-layered. These layers, analogous to those in the human body, are not next to each other, but rather concentrations that can all occupy the same space at the same time. The primal element fire is present everywhere and permeates the <em>bumi </em>and the<em> langit, </em>just as the primal form of the other elements does. Therefore, the <em>dewas </em>can live anywhere, in the air, in the water, or in the ground. Their bodies do not have a fixed form and cannot get sick, break, or be cut into pieces.</p><p>The <em>dewas</em> have an ego personality. Their self-consciousness comes from a force called the <em>kamayan </em>or<em> maya</em>, which is the same as the<em> kamayan</em> of the human body. They do not have a<em> Roh Suci</em> as an essential part, as humans do. Nor are they given <em>Suksma Sejati</em> to guide them as the True Leader.</p><p>Through the <em>kamayan, </em>the<em> dewas </em>have power and special abilities. They are therefore purely material. They can be compared to a battery charged with a certain amount of energy. The<em> kamayan </em>of the<em> dewas</em> diminishes over time and</p><p>—-------(1)</p><p>(1) Soenarto c.s.: S.D. Hoofdstuk „Gumelaring Dumadi", blz. 70—73.</p><p>-91-</p><p>eventually disappears, just as a battery gradually runs out. Then, their bodies return to the element of fire in the universe. Therefore, there is an age limit. The life of a <em>dewa </em>is a thousand times longer than that of a human. For example, if a human's age is 60 years, then a <em>dewa's </em>age is 60,000 years. The number of <em>dewas </em>is many times greater than that of humans, and due to the differences in <em>kamayan</em> potential, they form hierarchical relationships. They also form groups and societies according to their nature and life circumstances.<em> Dewas</em> who live in the water, the ground, or the forest each form communities with a kind of king, government, and subjects.</p><p>There are two large groups, the good and the evil. The good belong to the <em>Wisnu </em>group, also called<em> Sura, </em>and the evil to the<em> Kala </em>group, also called <em>Asuras. </em>They are constantly in conflict with each other. The<em> dewas, </em>through the<em> kamayan, </em>have knowledge of the machinery of life</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>around them, but their awareness does not extend beyond the material-bound, which can also be reached by our thinking alone.</p><p>The <em>dewas </em>with a large dose of<em> kamayan</em> have incredible power and control over everything that is material. Through this special power, they recognize themselves as the highest in life and think they rule the universe. Although the highest among the <em>Wisnu </em>group know of the existence of<em> Suksma Kawekas, </em>they do not recognize<em> Suksma Kawekas </em>as the Highest due to the nature of their being. Their self-sovereignty is so great that knowing that <em>Suksma Kawekas </em>is the Source of Life does nothing to diminish that self-sovereignty. They can only recognize themselves as a power above which no other power is conceivable. This quality is inherent in sovereignty.</p><p>The<em> Kala </em>group refuses to recognize <em>Suksma Kawekas </em>as the Source of Life, and they are always trying to wipe out the<em> Wisnu</em> group. Hence the constant</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>struggle between them. The self-sovereignty of the <em>dewas</em> causes them to want to be worshipped, and to do so, they force the weak-</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-92-</p><p>er ones among them to become subjects, who also seek protection from the powerful ones. Thus, they establish kingdoms. The powerful live in the fire world with a rarefied concentration, while the lesser ones live in the ever-denser concentration.</p><p>There are seven hierarchical categories, and each category is further subdivided into seven subcategories.</p><p>The broad outline of the hierarchy, according to the booklet <em>"Tunggal Sabda", </em>is as follows:</p><p>I.</p><p>The highest group is that of the <em>"Luhur,"</em> who elevates themselves and are seen by their subjects as the almighty in the (material) universe. Their symbolic representation is a three-pointed star with a blue center: it is a parallel to the Holy Trinity and also the symbol of royal power over the subjects.</p><p>II.</p><p>This group is called <em>"Duta" </em>(meaning envoy) to designate the group that transmits the orders of the<em> "Luhur."</em></p><p>The order has two facets:</p><ol><li>The life-giving and creative.</li><li>The destructive, annihilating.</li></ol><p>The symbolic representation is a four-pointed star, as a shadow image of the human body, which consists of four elements and receives the Word of the <em>Tripurusa</em>. In the center, the core is green, as the sign of the bearer of the order of their lord, the <em>dewa Luhur.</em></p><p>III.</p><p>This group is called <em>"Wisesa" </em>(meaning having authority over) and is symbolically represented as a five-pointed star with many colors in it, as a shadow image of the five senses of man, through which man grasps the external</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-93-</p><p>world. This group is the level of jurisdiction in the name of the <em>"Luhur" </em>with a destructive tendency towards the subjects.</p><p>IV.</p><p>This group is called <em>"Hayu" </em>(meaning blessing), which holds the power of the creative and life-giving command of the</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>"Luhur" </em>in its hands. They are the bringers and executors of good things. In the symbol, they are represented as a six-pointed star, a shadow image of the<em> Tripurusa </em>with its corresponding reflections <em>(pangaribawa, prabawa, </em>and <em>kamayan)</em>. Hence, this group of devas leads the subjects to good and brings blessings.</p><p>V.</p><p>This group is called <em>"Kuwasa" </em>(meaning power) as the executor of the decision of the<em> "Wisesa" </em>group.</p><p>Their symbolic representation is a seven-pointed star, as a shadow image of the desires (<em>angen-angen</em>) and the four elements of the human body. Therefore, they exert a certain power, as a result of what the senses (<em>Wisesa</em>) have received. This group is the executor of the decision with a destructive tendency.</p><p>VI.</p><p>This group is called <em>"Dana" </em>(meaning provider) and is symbolically represented as an eight-pointed star, as a shadow image of the four desire-forces, each with opposing good and evil qualities. This <em>"Dana" </em>is subordinate to the <em>"Kuwasa" </em>who acts in the name of the "<em>Wisesa" </em>and brings evil, but at the same time also the executor of the <em>"Hayu"</em> group who brings good. Therefore, the command that contains something good goes from the <em>"Luhur" </em>to the <em>"Duta",</em> then <em>"Hayu", </em>and finally reaches the <em>"Dana". </em>The command that brings evil as punishment comes from the <em>"Luhur" </em>to the<em> "Duta", </em>then to the<em></em></p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-94-</p><p><em>"Wisesa" </em>then <em>"Kuwasa", </em>and finally ends up with the<em> "Dana"</em>. This group leads and instructs the other smaller devas in their social order.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>VII.</p><p>The last group is the largest and forms the common people among the devas and is called <em>"Pada"</em> (meaning closer, point). They are symbolized by an image, as a representation of the most coarse and material among the devas.</p><p><em>Contact with Humans</em></p><p>Contact between humans and devas is possible only from the side of the devas. A human cannot on their own enter or gain knowledge of the world of the devas, unless guided by <em>Suksma Sejati. </em>The devas who frequently come into contact with humans belong to the group of <em>"Dana" </em>and<em> "Pada". </em>Through their <em>kamayan </em>or<em> maya, </em>they are able to connect with humans via the <em>angen-angen. </em>In the <em>angen-angen </em>of humans, the devas can conjure up any images they desire. They have, as it were, the<em> angen-angen</em> in their power. Humans can be influenced by these mental images, either if the images correspond to the expectations of the person involved, or if the images directly affect the executive organs. After all, humans control their bodies with their <em>angen-angen</em> images. The point of entry is "between the eyes" in the forehead. (Compare "The Secret of the Golden Flower" on the basic concept of Tao, p. 41).</p><p>The sovereignty of the devas, apart from making them feel almighty, also makes them want to be worshipped. The near presence of a deva of a slightly higher order is felt by man as a feeling of being the highest and "having no one above him".</p><p>The awareness of absolute sovereignty induces the ego-sovereignty of the <em>angen-angen </em>and tries to snatch it away from the harmonizing influence of the <em>Rahsa Jati</em>,</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-95-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>which can destroy faith in the <em>Tripurusa</em>. The person who experiences this has a feeling of being "crazy" and eventually becomes "crazy" indeed.</p><p>When a human forms images in their devotion to <em>Suksma Sejati </em>of how <em>Suksma Sejati </em>or the state of <em>Suksma Sejati </em>might be, it can happen that a deva manifests itself in those images in his thoughts, making the human slightly impressed, thinking he has achieved his expectation and thus giving his worship to the deva. Therefore, a human in his prayer and devotion must not form an image of the <em>Tripurusa </em>and its state, and the first commandment is to worship no one else but<em> Suksma Kawekas</em>. In the Old Testament, concerning "The Proclamation of the Ten Commandments" (Ex. 20) it says: 3. You shall have no other gods before me. 4. You shall not make for yourself an idol, nor any likeness of what is in heaven above, or what is on the earth beneath, or what is in the water under the earth.</p><p>The possession of a human by a deva can happen for good or for evil: for good when the human directs his worship towards a deva, and for evil when he does not. Letting oneself go in fantasies, daydreams, and reveries reserves a seat for the deva, as it were. The human then becomes possessed.</p><p>In the awareness of and devotion to the <em>Tripurusa, </em>it is expressed that the human body is the vehicle of the <em>Tripurusa, </em>where omnipotence shines forth, keeping the devas at a distance. The expulsion of a deva from a human body therefore happens with the consciousness and omnipotence of <em>Suksma Sejati </em>[in the name of <em>Suksma Kawekas</em>]<em>.</em></p><p>A person who is influenced by a deva avoids contact with people who are true in their devotion to <em>Suksma Sejati </em>and shuns the teachings of <em>Suksma Sejati</em>. Such a person receives the teachings of the deva as whispers in the ear or as images that can be perceived with his subtle sense of sight. The presence of a deva can be made known to the human by a specific smell or a certain feeling.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-96</p><p>The devas, on their part, try to tempt people to worship them. In return, they give what people crave, such as special knowledge that other people don't possess, for example, healing power, clairvoyance, or mastery of the body. This clairvoyance is not true clairvoyance, but the person repeats what the deva whispers or conjures for them. This is also how it goes with the other abilities. The deva uses the person more or less as a puppet. Once contact is established, the deva can be summoned by certain formulas and ceremonies (each deva has its own "key"), and the person acts as a medium for the deva. In those moments, the person may remain conscious or lose consciousness. While the deva is inside the person, they will experience a feeling of being almighty and above everyone else. The deva uses the executive organs to make itself known. The deva always remains felt as a foreign body in the personality. All this time, the possessed person has no say. The initiative is snatched away from them. Even when the possession is over, the uninitiative-taking climate hangs around for a while. If this drama happens often, then the person can be paralyzed in their angen-angen function and easily suggested to. We see a pseudo-intelligence because the person repeats what the deva whispers to them.</p><p>There are therefore two types of influence: 1. from a distance, where there is only sensory contact, and 2. through possession of the <em>angen-angen.</em></p><p>Following a deva, especially those of the higher orders, requires a way of life that outwardly does not differ from devotion to <em>Suksma Kawekas. </em>There too one finds worship with complete surrender, an asceticism that is truly difficult, and an attitude of detachment from the world, where a high character is necessary.</p><p>Where then does the difference lie?</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>—-------(-)</p><h2><a id="_cpn47u33mzj4"></a>-97-</h2><p>The Difference lies in the orientation of the ego and the sensations</p><p>The difference between worshipping devas and worshipping <em>Suksma Kawekas</em> lies in the orientation of the ego and the sensations experienced. When worshipping devas, the focus is outside the self, while devotion to <em>Suksma Kawekas </em>resides deep within the self, independent of any organ. This outward orientation leads to sensory encounters between humans and devas.</p><p>Entering the<em> Rahsa Jati </em>is never a sensory experience. Even messages from<em> Suksma Sejati</em> in the form of intuitions or revelations are not sensory.</p><p>During worship of devas, the ego-consciousness remains active and is even strengthened by encountering the deva's ego-sovereignty.</p><p>However, in Liberation, the human's ego-consciousness disappears. It is replaced by the <em>Tripurusa</em>, a higher-level, integrated functioning center.</p><p>Devas are always felt as foreign bodies within the human body, hindering all functions and disrupting harmony.</p><p>In contrast, the manifestation of S<em>uksma Sejati </em>is a metamorphosis of the entire personality. It harmonizes the centers and maximizes their potential. During an encounter with devas, humans might feel an "I am the highest" sensation, emphasizing their ego-sovereignty.</p><p>Unification with<em> Suksma Sejati </em>does not involve physical sensations. The <em>angen-angen</em> is in a state of devotional rest during this process.</p><p>Messages from devas are received through the senses, granting humans pseudo-special abilities, powers they essentially borrow from the devas.</p><p>Intuitions and revelations, on the other hand, originate from the <em>Tripurusa</em>, an essential part of the human. They represent the unfolding of one's own capacity.</p><p>Worshiping devas actually diminishes humans</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-98-</p><p>because they inherently possess greater power. The essence of humanity is Life itself, which even created the devas.</p><p>The human being elevates himself through devotion to <em>Suksma Kawekas </em>via <em>Suksma Sejati</em> to impersonal Personality.</p><p>To understand the further consequences of worshiping the devas, we must first illuminate the opinion</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>about life after death, as it is presented in this Indonesian image of man.</p><p>—------(-)</p><p>-99-</p><p>VIII ON LIFE AFTER DEATH</p><p>(1)</p><p>Death is considered a transition phase to another world. This "becoming different" has various perspectives. Death is a special opportunity in a person's life to suddenly and permanently shift their center of gravity to the <em>Tripurusa. </em>During the process of dying, the gate that leads to the<em> Rahsa Jati </em>stands wide open, as it were. The "I" only needs to enter. In other words,</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Suksma Sejati</em> calls the person back to their Primordial Existence. The moment of death is therefore a unique opportunity to enter Liberation, to detach oneself from the gross and subtle bodies. If Liberation occurs at death, then the person is freed from affinity for the gross and subtle bodies, both of which return to matter. The consciousness of the person returns to the immaterial Life.</p><p>If death has occurred and the person has not yet freed themselves from the affinity of the material, then the opportunity is missed. What happens then is only the process of separation of the gross and subtle bodies. The gross body decomposes and the constituent elements return to their original form.</p><p>The subtle body continues to exist and carries on the life of the deceased in a different state of being.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All vitality centers are still present. The gross senses, as a bridge between the personality and the external world, are no longer present. The external world as a factor for gaining experiences, necessary for the process of Liberation, has fallen away. This means that the person is now dependent on themselves and what is present within themselves. The intrapsychic life continues peacefully, mental images appear and disappear, desires, wishes, and impulses of will</p><p>—-------(1)</p><p>(1) Soenarto c.s.: S.D Hoofdstuk „Sangkan Paran”, blz. 175—194.</p><p>-100-</p><p>flicker constantly, and affects alternate as they did before death.</p><p>If, during his life before death, a human has never oriented himself and been able to create any order in his intrapsychic life, and never tried to find the way through the chaos of his own vital function products towards the <em>Rahsa Jati,</em> he will be even more helpless after death than before.</p><p>He becomes a plaything of <em>ngen-angen </em>(mind), <em>pangrasa </em>(feelings), <em>nafsu </em>activities (drives). In this circumstance, the usefulness of the external world and the gross physical body comes sharply to the fore.</p><p>Firstly, in the gross physical world, perceived by our senses and with which we are sensorily connected, there are people and situations that can help us in the process of Liberation, as an essential development of human-being as an individual. The interaction between the external world and the human is the basis for gaining experiences. In the encounter with the external world, corrections to one's own personality are possible and we can sensually verify examples that are useful for refreshing our sense of conscience. Also, fulfilling, materializing our desires is necessary for the life traveler to relieve tensions and neutralize the associated affects that arise from the continuous activity of the <em>nafsu</em>, which is further stimulated by the <em>angen-angen.</em></p><p>In the external world, there are objects available to react to our feelings of duty, responsibility, love and their polar opposites.</p><p>Subjectifying things in the external world, establishing a subjective relationship between the self and the external world, discharges the accumulating affective burden. It is as if the burden is then shared by both the self and the external world. Desubjectification completely shifts the burden onto the self. The human stands on his own, he is</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-101-</p><p>independent. Subjectification is a sign of weakness, desubjectification of spiritual growth.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>People who have much more experience than us in the process of Liberation, and even those who have achieved Liberation, can be present with us in the material world at the same time and help us put our own personalities in order. In short, the material life facilitates the path to the <em>Tripurusa.</em></p><p>This material world is called the sensory-spacial world by K. Jaspers. In the existence after death, isolation from the sensory-spatial world becomes a structural and functional fact. Under these conditions, the person becomes completely autistic and cannot make normal contact with the outside world. Furthermore, only those who died during the moment of death and could not follow the Call of <em>Suksma Sejati</em> live in that world. Even if they could still maintain contact with each other, they wouldn't be able to help each other either.</p><p>These deceased think and feel that they are still living as before. It's just that there is no object in an external world where they can react to their desires, cravings, and affects. Their thoughts and feelings become realities for them, but they can never bring satisfaction. Therefore, with the constant disappearance of those thoughts and feelings, they experience endless disappointments. For example, they may feel thirsty, but they cannot drink, and the thirst persists until it disappears on its own, because other feelings take its place. Perhaps they feel hot without being able to find shelter, or they yearn for their family without being able to be with them, or their family does not respond to their calls and presence. All these changes in desires and feelings that cannot be satisfied and that have to disappear on their own constitute a true torture. This continues until they finally seek the solution and liberation</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-102-</p><p>deep within themselves in a surrender to <em>Suksma Kawekas</em>. At that moment, they are freed.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>The world where they wander in the subtle body is called the dark world or <em>alam kafiruna</em>. It is a period of suffering, pain, and disappointments. These people live in a world of their wishful images, which they take for real materiel beings. In this world, which is nothing but a continuation of their intrapsychic life in the gross physical body, they are forced to seek the solution within themselves. The sooner this happens, the faster they get out of <em>alam kafiruna. </em>The play of <em>angen-angen </em>(mind), <em>pangrasa</em> (feelings), and nafsu (drives) was already underway in the gross physical life.</p><p>So, then, humans actually got a foretaste of <em>alam kafiruna</em>, but before death, the external world was there to react to all tensions and affects, to fulfill desires, and to practice finding the way back through the deepest part of the self. Whether someone ends up in <em>alam kafiruna </em>and how long they stay there depends on their life in the gross physical body.</p><p>The affinity for the worldly makes humans unaware of their inner duty at the moment of death. If they cannot shake off the worldly at the right moment, the preserved world goes with them and makes it impossible for them to detach from the subtle body. This body has no metabolism in <em>alam kafiruna </em>and is not bound by an age limit. The random disintegration of the subtle body in<em> alam kafiruna</em> can happen at any moment.</p><p>If the <em>Rahsa Jati</em> is found again, then the subtle body is discarded like an old garment. It happens just like in prayer in the gross physical life, where humans enter the sphere of <em>Rahsa Jati</em> and detach themselves from the existence of the body. Only in the latter case, after prayer, the ego-life returns to the same body.</p><p>In the <em>alam kafiruna, </em>the subtle body is permanently</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-103-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>left behind once the<em> Rahsa Jati</em> is entered. Here in this phase, the person is figuratively weighed and judged. If there is still an affinity for the worldly, then the personality is reborn into another reincarnation. Before being reborn again, he remembers the Confession once more and knows what awaits him in the next life. In this phase, the personality cannot withdraw and prefer to stay in the sphere of <em>Rahsa Jati, </em>but instead enters the next reincarnation immediately. He is born again as a human to complete the process of Liberation. Thus, humans have seven chances to reside in this world in a gross physical body to complete their Liberation. The<em> alam kafiruna </em>becomes increasingly darker with each subsequent time, and the subtle body becomes thinner. If after the seventh and final time he still ends up in the<em> alam kafiruna, </em>the person has strayed so far from the path of<em> Suksma Sejati</em> that it is almost impossible to remember <em>Suksma Sejati. </em>The redemption happens in an eighth reincarnation, according to the book<em> "Sangkan Paran"</em> by Soenarto et al., as stillborn children or children who die immediately after birth, or as some kind of large animal to atone for the animalistic way of life they led when they were still human.</p><p>As mentioned above, humans in this gross physical body already have a foretaste of the<em> alam kafiruna </em>when they are tormented by specific desires, thoughts, and feelings. This requires a life attitude towards what is present in the psyche, and thus towards the self, in the way it is marked out in the Pancasila.</p><p>Temen (courage) gives the courage to observe one's own self (truthfulness) in its true proportions, whether it turns out good or worthless. <em>Narima </em>(acceptance) and<em> sabar (patience, perseverance) </em>are there to accept the obtained results, not to be impatient and persistent in attaining those desires, while <em>rila </em>is the willingness to detach from the subjectively valuable in accumulated experiences, which makes desubjectification possible. <em>Budi luhur</em> is the quality as background, example, and conscience that contains hope: a possibility of being, as Carp expresses it, that is indeed attainable. This <em>budi luhur </em>brings us to the status of <em>Suksma Sejati. </em>If in prayer we become one with <em>Suksma Sejati </em>even once, we always see that we fall back to the previous level. We do not maintain ourselves in the state of <em>Suksma Sejati </em>for long at first, because there is still an affinity for the world clinging to us. We are not yet purified enough then. This phenomenon also occurs in the <em>alam kafiruna. </em>If humans have been able to leave autism through the self, they are thrown back into the world, as it were, if their purification is insufficient. However, they do not return to the <em>alam kafiruna, </em>but receive a complete physical body by being born again as a baby. Devotion to<em> Suksma Kawekas via Suksma Sejati</em> and the meaning of prayer are important points in this Indonesian image of humanity.</p><p>However, a person does not always direct his devotion to the Life that has its communication point deep within the self between the inner and outer world, but lets his happiness and future depend on spatial and temporal perspectives outside himself. For such a person, death has a completely different meaning, and he will have to learn to "pray" in the forced autistic life in <em>alam kafiruna.</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-105-</p><p>Besides attracting the devotion of humans outward from their self, the gods strengthen ego sovereignty and gradually loosen the connection between the <em>Rahsa Jati </em>and the material vitality centers. The thinner their subtle body becomes, the higher they come in the god's world, but the darker their mind becomes, seen from the viewpoint of the <em>Tripurusa. </em>The return to the<em> Tripurusa </em>becomes almost impossible. Such a person is still autistic, only the contact with the god occasionally breaks through their autism, but this contact will not give them a sufficient answer in the game of rising and falling desires, feelings, and memories, which always lead to disappointment. They can remain in the <em>alam kafiruna </em>for thousands and thousands of years. The god prevents them from converting to devotion to<em> Suksma Kawekas</em>. Thus, they only exceptionally come to be reborn in a gross physical body to be revived, where purification and impurity can coexist. Here they can contribute to gaining experiences to come closer and closer to <em>Suksma Sejati </em>and consciously experience Him, yes, where they</p><p>—-------(-)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>-106-</p><p>can even enter and leave the <em>Rahsa Jati</em> with the same body for the service of humanity.</p><p>The power of the deities often attracts and blinds humans so much that they forget their sacred Origin. ON KARMA (1)</p><p>Karma is a facet of <em>Suksma Kawekas, </em>which governs all materially bound life, as a law of Justice that determines that every action is reflected back. By action here is meant not only an activity of the body's motor apparatus, but also any deviation from the resting point in the vitality centers: <em>Rahsa Jati, angen-angen, pangrasa, </em>and <em>nafsu</em>. All properties of this deviation are subject to this law, such as quality, quantity, form, direction, in short, everything that is spatially and temporally bound.</p><p>What falls outside Karma is the immaterial Life, which is the Silence.</p><p>Buddha says: "Everything that arises, is born, or is made, carries within it the moral responsibility of destruction." Arising implies that it returns to the primordial existence. The act of entering (into a time and space existence) determines the exit.</p><p>If we examine the history of the universe's formation, then according to this Indonesian image of humanity (<em>Gumelaring Dumadi, </em>part II of <em>"Sasangka Djati"</em>), from the immaterial Life, which is Silence, the Dynamism is born as the Executor of the Will, which lies within that Silence. There has been a Will to separate<em> Roh Suci </em>as a spark of the Silence, but that Will waits in its execution for a material garment to receive the spark offered from the Self.</p><p>For this purpose, the Dynamic as the Executor of the Static creates the four primary elements in the order: <em>swasana</em> (aether, air), fire, water, and earth, each with its own specific power. With the birth of the <em>swasana,</em> time and space are born. Everything that arises after the primary element swasana and is materially bound is subject to spatial and temporal measurability. The</p><p>—-------(1)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(1) Soenarto c.s.: S.D. Hoofdstuk „Sangkan Paran”, blz. 194—263.</p><p>-108-</p><p>four elements interact with each other through their forces and under a fixed Plan, forming shapes and relationships that gradually give the Universe its appearance. When the receiving body is ready, the content follows: humans, deities, animals, and plants.</p><p>The essence of man, the Tripurusa, the immaterial Life in the three phases, clings to the material with all its consequences. At that moment the law of Karma comes into effect. Because the <em>Tripurusa </em>is considered a point of rest, the shift of the center of gravity of life to the material life is a reality that must one day be leveled. The attachment to the material is lifted by a Release or Liberation.</p><p>In Carp's book <em>"Problemen van het Mens-zijn",</em> (Problems of Being Human), page 81, it is stated that<em> "eens zal de Verlossing komen"</em> (redemption will come one day).</p><p>All the activities of the <em>angen-angen</em>, pangrasa and nafsu are a consequence of the shift of the center of gravity to the materiel, a choice of a life with polar possibilities of being and action. This polarity does not exist in the <em>Tripurusa.</em></p><p>All three vitality centers show polarity.</p><p>The angen-angen is directed towards concentration and abstraction. An illumination by the<em> angen-angen</em> creates a shadow side outside the beam of light. Attention has limits and makes it obvious that there is an outside attention present. The formation of a consciousness is accompanied by the emergence of an unconsciousness.</p><p>The climate of the <em>Tripurusa, </em>which is called <em>Rahsa Jati, </em>is not what in daily life is consciousness or unconsciousness, but is the twilight between them, which contains both.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>This Consciousness of the <em>Tripurusa </em>does not dispel the consciousness of daily life, but is transcendent to consciousness and unconsciousness. The liberated man also sleeps, but is conscious during sleep, dies,</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-109-</p><p>but death does not touch this Consciousness and does not change anything in the Consciousness. In the terms of Karma, it is said that man then stands outside of Karma, outside of the law of cause and effect.</p><p>Thus, the <em>angen-angen </em>in sovereignty has a counterweight in submissiveness; in the powerful activity as regulator of the body, the counterweight is the powerless surrender as the passive towards the<em> Tripurusa.</em></p><p>The nafsu also has its polar characteristics. The<em> Lawamah</em> has two opposing characters that make sublimation possible. Moreover, the lawamah is a counterpoint to the <em>mutmainah</em>.</p><p>If we imagine the vitality centers as energy sources, as Jung suggests, then the outgoing energy "once" returns to the original center, in all qualities. One might be tempted to speak of a conservation of work capacity and to declare the laws of physics applicable to material-bound life.</p><p>The polar facets of one center can balance each other, but an activity once experienced can never be undone. If we compare two polar facets of one center with white and black ink that we put both in one vat, then the ratio of those two facets determines the color of the liquid. If there is little black and a lot of white, then at a certain point we see no black, but the black ink is definitely still there.</p><p>Therefore, there is an influence in the law of Karma, in the sense of a culmination and an enlightenment.</p><p>Through enlightenment and culmination, actions reflected to us by Karma can be felt lighter or heavier. The environment in which Karma comes to us is also very important. For example, if someone has hit another person on the head with a hammer, then according to Karma, they must also one day receive a blow to the head. It depends on their attitude and behavior between the time they gave the blow and the time they receive</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-110-</p><p>the Karma, how it comes to them. If they behave in the meantime while relying on a Consciousness of <em>Suksma Sejati </em>and live according to the<em> Trisila </em>and <em>Pancasila</em>, then this line of conduct levels down their previous actions. Seen from this point of view, the law of Karma, also "angger-angger langgeng" (forever valid, unchangeable law) is a symptom of the All-righteousness and at the same time Forgiveness of <em>Suksma</em></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><em>Kawekas </em>allows us to extract a summary of it through organic and spiritual experiences, which can then be used as a compass to find the essence of life. There is a pedagogical efficiency. For the life traveler who pursues this goal and has recognized the possibility of Union with Suksma Sedjati and Liberation from the law of Karma, there no happiness and unhappiness, Everything is experience. areThere are only actions and attitudes to life that keep him at the level of one</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-111-</p><p>materially bound life or that which provides him with Liberation. This polarity remains from placing the center of gravity permanently in the <em>Tripurusa</em> or in the physical body. Once the center of gravity has been permanently established in the immaterial Life, then the control of the body takes place from here. The actions of the body are then</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>manifestations of Suksma Sedjati, which is above Karma. If life in a material garment with its consequences is regarded as "sin" or at least contains a potential for "sin", then such a liberated person is delivered from "sin". Redeeming oneself from "sins" it is getting closer to the state of Suksma Sedjati. This does not mean that such a person confuses the concept of good and evil and tramples it underfoot, it only means that discrimination is no longer a consideration for him to orient himself in life.</p><p>A person who is just coming into life for the first time has no experience in handling their <em>angen-angen, pangrasa, </em>and<em> nafsu</em>.</p><p>Their vital functions are not yet based on experience, so such a person will easily be influenced by external factors and other people. Justice is therefore absolute and impersonal.</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-112-</p><p>Furthermore, it is stated in the same book “Sangkan Paran” that if Liberation has not yet occurred in the first</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>incarnation, and the human being enters a second life after experiencing the alam kafiruna, then in this second life the not yet accomplished Karma intertwined is like a future perspective.</p><p>In the second and potentially following lives, experiences accumulate, and more initiative and personal responsibility come into play. The Karma also determines in which layer of social life one may end up in the next reincarnation.</p><p>One can legitimately wonder whether it is correct that the true purpose of life is Liberation, as outlined here. As a person who has not yet been liberated, one certainly cannot give one conclusive answer. However, we can test the Truth of the TriPurusa by our own empiricism, by living a life that is predisposed to the intuitions or revelations. Or one can go the way of the dewas. Whatever one chooses, man is ultimately accountable only to himself.</p><p>Let's give our thoughts free rein for a moment.</p><p>Suppose it were true that Liberation was the purpose of life, then in the long run this would become more and more accentuated. Maybe, just maybe, because this one</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>—------(-)</p><p>-114-</p><p>train of thought is a train of thoughts alone, these two groups would one day come into conflict with each other.</p><p>If humanity's development has progressed to the point where only two differentiations remain, namely the group that manifests the <em>Tripurusa </em>within themselves and the opposing group that takes self-sovereignty to the extreme, then wouldn't the path to experiencing the <em>Tripurusa </em>be not a cumbersome<em> Trisila </em>and <em>Pancasila</em>, but simply a remembering of the Sovereignty of Life above oneself to belong to the first group? The completion of this inevitable fact is a physiological process, and as is the case with all physiological processes, there is something healing in its acceptance. To resist death is to be fixated on a phase associated with pleasure - the experience of living - which leads to neurotic reactions.</p><p>If collective consciousness is attained before physical death has entered, then we have the following. It manifests itself by using the executive organs, directly without an intermediate phase of an autonomous complex nature. The body no longer has</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>its own will or desire. Organic experiences such as hunger, sleep, physical fatigue, pain, defecation are no longer psychologically processed,</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-151-</p><p>but remain events as such in the organic level.</p><p>There are no longer remnants of emotional connections towards parents, friends, society, etc. The relationship of bondage has given way to a relationship of connection based on infinite affection on the part of the one who has reached this state. The veil hinders the light of the Tripurusa and gives off a light itself (that of the intellect and of feeling sovereign), which is different from the light of the Tripurusa</em>.</p><p>In the state of the <em>Bayu Sejati</em>, there is an optimal deliberate bundling of the 3 centers by the ego. Because it is arbitrary, it falls within the scope of the experiment.</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-155-</p><p>I I THERAPEUTIC PERSPECTIVES OF THE INDONESIAN IMAGE OF MAN</p><p>If we are aware that the original intention of the Indonesian image of man for Soenarto and his two associates was to find the way to liberation, then we have seen that the process of liberation involves actively accepting the progression in the development of the human psyche. (2)</p><p>This state of consciousness is absolute peace, which (3) is unknowable in psychic experience.</p><p>If we call the state of the fetus in utero paradisical, then we can also call the state of the collective conscious paradisical. Hoofdstuk „Dalan Rabaju”, blz 162.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>-157-</p><p>within the self; the ego can enter the immaterial or experience the encounter with the hermit when it has undergone the (meditative) states of consciousness. We recognize here the "Individuation" of Jung (6).</p><p>As long as the struggle has not been successfully ended, the problem for both the "healthy" and the "neurotic" person in the Indonesian image of man is basically the same.</p><p>How does the Indonesian image of man, in general terms, approach the problem of not succumbing in the struggle?</p><p>Firstly: Accepting an attainable possibility of being in this life, in which there is a perspective of an eternal, paradise-like experience on another level.</p><p>Secondly: Letting go of the pleasurable phase, to which the physical being tries to cling and relive again and again.</p><p>The implementation of this is described in the successive chapters of the original book "Sasangka Jati", which we can summarize as follows:</p><p>1. Maintaining the state one has reached, meaning maintaining the neurosis-free state (<em>Dalan Rahayu</em>: Chapter V).</p><p>To motivate the self to leave a pleasurable phase and pursue a specific goal, which requires repeated exertion, there must be an expectation of gaining something better in return for what is left behind. The ego-consciousness stands between the world perceptible to the senses and the supersensible possibility of being.</p><p>Karl Jaspers, in his "Psychology of Worldviews," puts it this way: the ego, as the source of the cultural, stands in the "psychically-cultural" image of man between the "sensory-spatial" and the "metaphysical" image of man.</p><p>&lt;—————-- ik ——————&gt; wereld</p><p>————— fijnstoffelijk —————</p><p>———— seelisch-culturel ————</p><p>—-——— psychisch –—————</p><p>Through the <em>Pancasila </em>and the <em>Paliwara</em>, the ego tries to break free from its attachment to the world perceptible to the senses, the macrocosm, whose characteristic is change. It is a strength effort of the ego, which consciously steps over resistances and dares to face facts that could have negative consequences for the self.</p><p>The social consequence of the training to be truthful is the increase in reliability, integrity, courage, and the fact that others can rely on the person involved.</p><p>More important is the psychological consequence, which cultivates the courage to see one's own mistakes and then to view the momentary</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-163-</p><p>self-image of the personality against the framework of the conscience image. He further states: "Consciousness is attached to this ego, it controls the access to motility, i.e., to the discharge of excitations into the external world. It is the mental instance that exercises control over all its partial processes, that goes to sleep at night and then still maintains the dream censorship. From this ego also emanate the repressions, by which certain mental strivings are to be excluded not only from consciousness but also from the other modes of validity and activity."</p><p>On page 27, Freud writes: "It is easy to see that the ego is the part of the id that has been changed by the direct influence of the external world through the mediation of W-Bw., so to speak a continuation of the surface differentiation."</p><p>It follows that the ego is a product of the confluence and interaction of the id and the external world.</p><p>The "id," which is unconscious, is therefore primary for Freud. Because the ego has arisen from the id (through the influence of the external world), there is a connection between the ego and the id. Through this connection, there is an interaction, a reciprocal influence. After all, Freud says on page 27: "It (the ego) also endeavors to make the influence of the external world on the id and its intentions effective, and strives to put the reality principle in place of the pleasure principle, which reigns unrestricted in the id."</p><p>—-------(1)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(1) S. Freud: Das Ich und das Es. Internation. Psychoanal. Verlag. Leipzig, Wien, Zürich. 1973, blz. 14.</p><p>-179-</p><p>"The ego represents what can be called reason and prudence, in contrast to the id, which preserves the passions."</p><p>Although the ego is therefore a differentiation of the surface of the id, we also see a certain polarity between the ego and the id. This polarity is only possible if the ego and the id relate to each other as two autonomous centers or complexes and implies: conscious versus unconscious, reason and prudence versus passion.</p><p>In the id, the instincts reign unbridled. It is the sexual drive and the death drive that constantly want to manifest themselves. These manifestations are adapted by the ego to the demands of the reality of the external world. The reality principle is opposed to the pleasure principle, which wells up from the id, and the ego stands between them. The ego in Freud's system has a third opponent: the superego, which partly arises from the ego itself, but which on the other hand is fed by the id with phylogenetic precipitates.</p><p>The superego, also called the ego ideal, stands in opposition to the other contents of the ego, or rather of the conscious. In fact, on page 40 of the book: "Das Ich und das Es", Freud writes: "Thus, one can assume as the most general result of the sexual phase dominated by the Oedipus complex, a precipitate in the ego, which consists in the establishment of these two, somehow agreed upon ideal identifications. This change in the ego retains its special position: it opposes the other content of the ego as the ego ideal or superego."</p><p>Freud further elaborates on the superego and says on page 43: "What biology and the fate of mankind have created and left behind in the id, is taken over by the ego through ideal attachment and individually relived in it. As a result of its history of formation, the</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>ego ideal has the most extensive connection with the</p><p>—-------(-)</p><p>-180</p><p>phylogenetic acquisition, the archaic inheritance, of the individual."</p><p>Page 71: "The superego is indeed created through identification with the father figure. Every such identification has the character of a desexualization or self-sublimation."</p><p>Ethics, morality, and religion reside in this superego. However, all these facets arise from the confrontation of the id and the reality of the external world. Freud clarifies this on page 44: "As a substitute formation for the longing for the father, it contains the germ from which all religions have developed. The judgment of one's own inadequacy in comparing the ego with its ideal results in the humble religious feeling on which the yearning believer relies. In the further course of development, teachers and authorities have continued the father role; their commands and prohibitions have remained powerful in the ideal ego and now exercise moral censorship as conscience. The tension between the demands of conscience and the achievements of the ego is felt as a feeling of guilt."</p><p>Reality stands before the ego in two forms. Firstly, as the momentary reality in the external world, which can reach the ego through perception, and secondly, the internalized external world, which can influence the ego through experience as the superego.</p><p>The boundaries of the ego extend into the unconscious. However, consciousness has the ego as its core. Both towards the id and towards the superego, the ego becomes increasingly unconscious. We see this in Freud's statements on page 21: "Thinking in images is therefore only a very imperfect becoming conscious." And on page 30: "Not only the deepest, but also the highest in the ego can be unconscious (self-criticism, conscience, unconscious guilt feeling)."</p><p>Ultimately, the ego stands between 3 factors: the external world, the id, and the superego. Potentially, every person can reach this highest state of consciousness.</p><p>These things completely correspond with the viewpoint of the Indonesian human image, which assumes that in every human being the immaterial center, TriPurusa, is latently present, and that every person is potentially capable</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>of achieving the awareness of the TriPurusa. With this, Liberation is brought about. In Jung's "Individuationsprozess," it is also a liberation process in which the hero repeatedly has to fight the monster (56).</p><p>—-----(55-56)</p><p>(55) C. G. Unlike yoga, the object of consideration is the sporadic emergence of faint traces of imagination, whether they are images, whether they are feelings, which detach themselves from the dark background of invisibility of the unconscious, to at least appear shadow-like to the inwardly directed gaze. In this way, what is repressed and lost comes back again (61)."</p><p>Both systems speak of character changes and take into account the demands of society. Jung even lists some qualities, which in their application can be compared to the Pancasila in the Indonesian concept of humanity, namely "Patience, Love, Faith, Hope, and Humility" (62).</p><p>We cannot discuss Jung's concept of humanity without briefly addressing his ideas about the Animus and Anima. Jung starts from the premise that certain things in the world exist as virtual images innate in people.</p><p>"The form of the world into which he is born is already innate in him as a virtual image. And thus parents, wife, children, birth, and death are innate in him as virtual images, as psychic</p><p>—-------(61-62)</p><p>(61) C. G. Jung: Seelenprobleme der Gegenwart, Rascher &amp; Cie A.G.Verlag, Zürich, blz. 11.</p><p>(62) C. G. Jung: Die Psychologie der Übertragung, Zürich, 1946, blz. 228.</p><p>-216-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>predispositions. In a certain sense, they are the residues of all the experiences of the ancestors, but not those experiences themselves. There is an inherited collective image of woman in the unconscious of man, with the help of which he comprehends the essence of woman (63)."</p><p>This image of the woman in the unconscious of the man, Jung calls anima. "The animus is a kind of reflection of all the experiences of the female ancestors in men - and not only that: it is also a procreative creative being, although not in the form of male creativity, but it produces something that one could call a procreative word (64).”</p><p>In the Indonesian concept of a human being, women's traits that shine through in the background in men are not attributed to a virtual image of the woman, as a residue of experiences about the woman in the man, but those traits are inherently linked to a vitality centre, the pangrasa (feelings), which remains in the background in men. The man puts the emphasis on another vitality centre, the angen-angen or logos, which then comes to the foreground.</p><p>Conversely, the woman puts the emphasis of her attitude to life on the pangrasa, causing the angen-angen to be pushed to the background. The qualities of the angen-angen, which we can normally easily observe in men and therefore call male character traits, continue to shine through in the background in women.</p><p>In the Indonesian concept of a human being, therefore, the anima-animus phenomenon has nothing to do with phylogenetic experiences, but is brought about by shifts in life orientation in the presence of two compensatory vitality centres: the angen-angen and the pangrasa.</p><p>—-------(63-64)</p><p>(63) C.
